						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">DRW wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I didn't call it that.<br /></div><br />Sorry, I fixed my post.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I would still prefer the 31 and 255 calculation though. It just looks cleaner to me.</div><br />Both calculations sets a linear slope so that 0-&gt;0 and 31 -&gt; 255. But it all comes down to rounding, the version based on bit shifts ignores the bits shifted out, so it actually sets the second point to 31 -&gt; 255.75 because 2 set bits are shifted out on the right. So both can be seen as technically correct, it depends if you consider full white to be &quot;exactly&quot; 255 or if you consider it &quot;all bits set&quot; (including bits which are eventually dropped).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But shouldn't an emulator strive to be as accurate as possible and not use some cheapshots just because of a simple division?</div><br />ZSNES is definitely inaccurate - their goal were to run as many SNES games as possible on late-1990s PCs. It's pretty much the Nesticle of SNES emulation. As I said lazyness is the only reason I see why they didn't scale colours properly.<br />Since the screen is entirely a bit more dim, I guess the eyes just get used to it and see (240, 240, 240) as white, even though it's technically not the brightest possible colour.</div>

